Why
We
Picked
It
Acura’s
sporty
RDX
is
smaller
than
its
three-row
MDX
but
pulls
more
weight
on
the
leaderboard
as
the
brand’s
top-selling
model
and
has
been
a
segment
top
seller
for
five
years
straight.
The
current,
fourth-generation
RDX,
was
redesigned
from
the
ground
up
for
the
2019
model
year
and
sits
on
a
new
platform
that
gives
it
more
premium
proportions
and
athletic
handling.
It’s
now
powered
by
a
turbocharged
2.0-liter
inline-four
cylinder
engine
and
10-speed
automatic
transmission
that
delivers
272
horsepower
and
an
impressive
280
pound-feet
of
torque.
When
equipped
with
Acura’s
Super-Handling
All-Wheel-Drive
system
(SH-AWD),
the
RDX
is
even
more
agile
and
fun
to
drive.
Pros
&
Cons
Well-built
Great
standard
safety
tech
SH-AWD
is
fun
and
effective
Tricky
infotainment
controls
Tight
