Why
We
Picked
It
The
Jeep
Wrangler
compact-nearly-midsize
SUV
has
a
long
legacy
of
capability
and
distinctive
styling
that
screams
off-road
adventure.
Though
the
fourth-generation
Wrangler
is
still
at
home
on
dirt
trails,
it’s
well-mannered
on
the
road,
especially
with
its
available
2.0-liter
inline-four
cylinder
engine
with
eTorque
(mild
hybrid
assist
using
a
48-volt
battery)
and
stop/start
technology
that
upped
its
fuel
economy
game
over
previous
generations.
It’s
also
now
available
with
a
3.0-liter
V6
diesel
engine
and
forthcoming
is
a
plug-in
version
that
won’t
offer
many
all-electric
miles
(25
to
be
exact)
but
will
please
with
instant
low-end
torque
from
dual
electric
motors
(combined
output
is
375
horsepower
and
475
pound-feet
of
torque).
The
Wrangler
comes
in
numerous
trims
to
satisfy
the
needs
of
many,
including
its
Unlimited,
which
offers
four
doors.
Jeep
finally
delivered
on
the
diesel
and
also
maintained
the
rock-crawling
prowess
in
its
electrified
4xe
variant
without
revising
the
core
tenets
that
define
the
Wrangler:
four-wheel
drive,
short-overhangs,
high
ground
clearance
and
a
robust
driveline.
Pros
&
Cons
Unstoppable
off-road
capable
Well-mannered
on
road
Wide
range
of
personalization
Wind
and
tire
noise
at
highway
speeds
Ingress
can
be
tough
for
shorter
drivers
New
technology
may
be
a
turn
off
for
Wrangler
purists
