Why
We
Picked
It
The
two-row
Corsair
sits
below
the
Nautilus
and
is
Lincoln’s
smallest
and
least
expensive
crossover.
It
debuted
in
2020,
replacing
the
MKC.
It
shares
the
same
platform
as
the
Ford
Escape
but
separates
itself
with
a
more
premium
styling,
upscale
features
and
a
load
of
standard
safety
tech,
including
blind
spot
monitoring,
rear
cross-traffic
alerts,
automatic
emergency
braking,
lane
keeping
assistance
and
automatic
headlights.
It’s
clear
Lincoln
put
a
lot
of
thought
into
the
Corsair’s
interior
experience:
the
materials
are
plush,
the
lines
are
clean
and
the
layout
is
comfortable
and
inviting.
There
are
two
trims
of
the
Lincoln
Corsair
and
two
engines:
a
250-horsepower
2.0-liter
inline-four
cylinder
and
a
larger
2.3-liter
four-cylinder
with
295
horsepower.
It’s
expected
that
Lincoln
will
add
a
plug-in
hybrid
variant
with
an
estimated
266
horsepower
and
25
miles
of
pure
electric
range
in
the
near
future.
Pros
&
Cons
Gorgeous,
inside
and
out
Strong
optional
engine
Generous
standard
safety
features
Gets
expensive
fast
Somewhat
cramped
back
seat
Disconnected
driving
feel
