Why
We
Picked
It
The
Nissan
Rogue
compact
crossover
is
an
important
vehicle
to
the
automaker
and
it’s
not
hard
to
see
why:
last
year
it
sold
over
200,000
units
and
it’s
still
nipping
at
the
heels
of
the
Toyota
RAV4
and
Honda
CR-V,
which
currently
are
kings
of
the
mainstream
compact
crossover
court.
The
Rogue,
which
has
always
doubled
proficiently
as
a
dependable
daily
driver
and
weekend
warrior,
underwent
some
major
changes
for
the
2021
model
year
that
make
it
a
good
choice
for
more
than
its
reliability.
A
clean,
modern
design,
a
new
2.5-liter
inline-four
cylinder
engine,
a
refined
ride
quality
(thanks
to
its
significantly
stiffer
structure
and
revised
suspension)
and
an
upgraded
interior
make
this
Rogue
feel
way
more
grown
up.
It’s
also
generously
loaded
with
standard
safety
tech,
including
automatic
emergency
braking
with
pedestrian
and
cyclist
detection,
rear
automatic
braking
and
an
intelligent
driver
alertness
system.
Driver
warnings
for
crossing
outside
of
lane
markers,
objects
in
the
blind
spots
and
potential
forward
and
rear
collisions
also
are
on
the
list.
Pros
&
Cons
Supremely
comfortable
seats
Family-friendly
to
the
max
Refined
driving
dynamics
Too
much
wind
and
road
noise
Could
use
a
few
more
horsepower
Top
trims
get
expensive
Specs
