Why
We
Picked
It
The
RAV4
is
the
compact
crossover
that
could.
Known
by
many
industry
insiders
as
the
first-ever
crossover
in
existence,
the
RAV4
surpassed
Toyota’s
lineup-leading
Camry
sedan
and
became
the
No.
1
best-selling
vehicle
in
the
U.S.
that
isn’t
a
pickup.
Now
in
its
fifth
generation,
the
Japanese
automaker
has
given
some
big
attention
to
its
little
crossover,
transitioning
it
from
a
fuel-sipping
hatchback
to
a
daring
adventurer—it
has
8.4
inches
of
ground
clearance
and
all-wheel
drive
with
pre-set
modes
for
varying
terrain.
It
also
has
a
new
TRD
Off
Road
variant,
which
officially
includes
it
in
the
truck
family
to
which
the
rock-crawling
4Runner,
Tacoma,
Tundra
and
Sequoia
belong.
Toyota
also
added
a
plug-in
hybrid
model,
the
RAV4
Prime,
which
some
claim
is
indeed
the
“prime”
RAV4
to
buy.
With
so
many
configurations
available,
it’s
bound
to
please
a
wide
range
of
drivers.
Pros
&
Cons
Lots
of
trims
and
drivetrain
combinations
Multiple
drive
modes
give
it
an
extra
boost
on
snow
Seats
and
dash
made
of
durable
materials
to
withstand
dirty
adventures
Slow
off
the
line
Underwhelming
drive
experience
in
gas
version
Base
model
is
bare
bones
