Why
We
Picked
It
The
Volvo
XC40
subcompact
crossover
is
the
smallest
and
newest
member
of
Volvo’s
SUV
lineup
and
also
has
the
most
distinct
styling,
with
a
boxier,
more
youthful
design
than
the
larger
XC60
and
XC90
SUVs.
It
also
is
the
first
Volvo
to
use
the
Compact
Modular
Architecture,
which
was
purposefully
developed
by
the
automaker
for
use
in
global
small
car
production.
The
XC40
is
offered
in
three
trims
(Momentum,
R-Design
and
Inscription)
with
a
turbocharged
2.0-liter
four-cylinder
engine
that
delivers
either
187
or
248
horsepower.
The
punchier
engine
is
only
available
with
an
all-wheel
drivetrain.
Another
fun
fact
about
the
XC40
that
further
separates
it
from
its
peers
is
that
it
represents
Volvo’s
push
into
electrification.
An
all-electric
variant,
the
XC40
Recharge,
joined
the
lineup
for
2021,
setting
the
precedent
for
electric
expansion
across
the
lineup.
Pros
&
Cons
Contemporary
design
Stable
handling
3,500-pound
towing
capacity
when
properly
equipped
Unimpressive
fuel
economy
Small
cargo
area
Complicated
infotainment
submenus
